                <h2>Scene: A Late-Night Urgent Call</h2>
<p>At 2 AM, Lao Wang, the performance marketing lead at a home goods export company, received a notification: Facebook had rejected his ad account due to "payment method verification failure." He scrolled through his WeChat history and found that the agent had said "being processed" three days earlier, but there was no specific progress update.</p>
<p>This isn't an isolated case. He manages 8 ad platforms and 12 agents, with over 40 account opening, top-up, and renewal tasks monthly—all tracked through Excel and chat records.</p>
<p>This isn't a capability issue—it's a process management issue.</p>
<h2>Problem Breakdown: Four Efficiency Black Holes in Agency Account Management</h2>
<h3>1. Progress Black Box: No Visibility into Blockers</h3>
<p>Agency account opening involves multiple stages: document submission, platform review, payment verification, and more. When an agent says "still processing," there's no way to know if it's stuck on document supplementation, platform queue, or payment issues. Many teams only discover problems when accounts are "dead."</p>
<h3>2. Top-up Delays: Discovering Empty Balances Too Late</h3>
<p>Ad account balances shouldn't be replenished after depletion. They need proactive warnings. But with manual multi-account management, accounts are often suspended before teams notice—recoveries can take 24-48 hours, directly impacting campaign schedules.</p>
<h3>3. Account Status Chaos: Who's Running What</h3>
<p>A utility app team once mistakenly topped up "North America" budget into the "Southeast Asia" account due to management confusion, disrupting campaigns in both markets. The correspondence between accounts, budgets, markets, and agencies relies on human memory, which inevitably fails.</p>
<h3>4. Financial Reconciliation Difficulties: Monthly Confusion</h3>
<p>End-of-month reconciliations require teams to verify recharge records, opening fees, and balance changes with agents line by line. Manual verification has high error rates and consumes significant time, diverting focus from core advertising work.</p>
<h2>Judgment: Why These Problems Recur</h2>
<p>These four problems share a common root cause: <strong>the lack of a visual task status tracking system</strong>.</p>
<p>When an account opening request is submitted, its status changes (pending submission, under review, awaiting top-up, live, suspended) should be trackable in a centralized system rather than scattered across chat records. The core value of kanban tools is making every task's status instantly visible.</p>
<h2>Action: Four Key Steps to Kanban Management</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Establish Standardized Task Columns</h3>
<p>Kanban columns correspond to key stages in the account opening process:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Documents Pending</strong>: Waiting for operations to provide credentials</li>
<li><strong>Agent Processing</strong>: Documents delivered, awaiting agent submission</li>
<li><strong>Platform Review</strong>: Awaiting Meta, Google, TikTok, etc. approval</li>
<li><strong>Top-up Pending Confirmation</strong>: Post-approval, awaiting finance confirmation</li>
<li><strong>Account Active</strong>: Live and running</li>
<li><strong>Exception/Suspended</strong>: Needs resolution</li>
</ul>
<p>Each task card includes: client name, agency, platform, budget amount, creation time, expected completion time.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Set Automated Alert Rules</h3>
<p>For balance alerts:</p>
<ul>
<li>Balance below 20% of budget → Card marked as "Warning"</li>
<li>Balance below 10% → Auto-notify lead and finance</li>
<li>Balance unchanged for 3 consecutive days → Trigger investigation</li>
</ul>
<p>After implementing a kanban system, one cross-border e-commerce team reduced balance-depletion suspensions from 6-8 times monthly to 1-2 times.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Close the Communication Loop with Agencies</h3>
<p>Don't let agencies respond "being processed" via WeChat. Instead:</p>
<ul>
<li>Require agencies to update status on kanban cards</li>
<li>Each status change includes notes explaining progress</li>
<li>When blocked, communicate directly on the card, preserving complete records</li>
</ul>
<p>This way, the team lead can open the kanban anytime and see the full processing history of each account.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Automate Monthly Reconciliation</h3>
<p>With kanban integrated with financial data, monthly reports auto-generate:</p>
<ul>
<li>Recharge summaries by agency</li>
<li>Balance change details by platform</li>
<li>Opening fees and renewal records</li>
</ul>
<p>Operations only needs to verify if numbers match, rather than manual line-by-line statistics.</p>
<h2>Results: Efficiency Gains Are Visible</h2>
<p>Three months after implementing kanban management, data from a gaming export team:</p>
